hip between the one and the many. While cultural and literary scholars have attributed the metaphor to late nineteenth-century germ theory or immunology, this book offers a new, more expansive history stretching from the metaphor's roots in early nineteenth-century militarism to its consolidation during the rise of early twentieth-century pharmacology. In so doing, Servitje establishes literature's pivotal role in shaping what war has made thinkable and actionable under medicine's increasing jurisdiction in our lives. Medicine Is War reveals how, in our own moment, the metaphor remains conducive to harming as much as healing, to control as much as empowerment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDiseases in literature. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMedicine in literature. 0aMedicine, MilitaryzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aWar in literature. 0aWarxMedical aspects. 4aArea Studies : British Studies. 4aLiterature : English Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary History. 4aLiterature : Nineteenth-Century Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848169240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438481692423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438481692/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles